# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: powershell-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:powershell-deep/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell is bundled with current versions of Windows and can be installed on macOS and Linux.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Since Windows 10 build 14971, PowerShell replaced Command Prompt as the default command shell exposed by File Explorer.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In PowerShell, administrative tasks are generally performed via *cmdlets* (pronounced *command-lets*), which are specialized .NET classes implementing a particular operation.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] These work by accessing data in different data stores, like the file system or Windows Registry, which are made available to PowerShell via *providers*.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Third-party developers can add cmdlets and providers to PowerShell.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Cmdlets may be used by scripts, which may in turn be packaged into modules.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Cmdlets work in tandem with the .NET API.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell's support for .NET Remoting, WS-Management, CIM, and SSH enables administrators to perform administrative tasks on both local and remote Windows systems.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell also provides a hosting API with which the PowerShell runtime can be embedded inside other applications.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] These applications can then use PowerShell functionality to implement certain operations, including those exposed via the graphical interface.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] This capability has been used by Microsoft Exchange Server 2007 to expose its management functionality as PowerShell cmdlets and providers and implement the graphical management tools as PowerShell hosts which invoke the necessary cmdlets.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Other Microsoft applications including Microsoft SQL Server 2008 also expose their management interface via PowerShell cmdlets.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell includes its own extensive, console-based help (similar to man pages in Unix shells) accessible via the `Get-Help` cmdlet.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Updated local help contents can be retrieved from the Internet via the `Update-Help` cmdlet.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Alternatively, help from the web can be acquired on a case-by-case basis via the `-online` switch to `Get-Help`.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Shell programs, including PowerShell, trace lineage to shells in older operating systems such as MS-DOS and Xenix which exposed system functionality to the user almost exclusively via a command-line interface (CLI) – although MS-DOS 5 also came with a complementary graphical DOS Shell.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The Windows 9x family came bundled with COMMAND.COM, the command-line environment of MS-DOS.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The Windows NT and Windows CE families, however, came with the newer cmd.exe – a significant upgrade from COMMAND.COM.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Both environments provide CLI for both internal and external commands and automation via batch files – a relatively primitive language for scripting.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] To address limitations of these shells – including the inability to directly use a software component exposed via COM – Microsoft introduced the Windows Script Host in 1998 with Windows 98, and its command-line based host, `cscript.exe`.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] It integrates with the Active Script engine and allows scripts to be written in compatible languages, such as JScript and VBScript.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] These scripts can use COM components directly, but it has relatively inaccessible documentation and gained a reputation as a system vulnerability vector after several high-profile computer viruses exploited weaknesses in its security provisions.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Different versions of Windows provided various special-purpose command-line interpreters (such as netsh and WMIC) with their own command sets but they were not interoperable.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Windows Server 2003 further attempted to improve the command-line experience but scripting support was still unsatisfactory.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] By the late 1990s, Intel had come to Microsoft asking for help in making Windows, which ran on Intel CPUs, a more appropriate platform to support the development of future Intel CPUs.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] At the time, Intel CPU development was accomplished on Sun Microsystems computers which ran Solaris (a Unix variant) on RISC-architecture CPUs.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The ability to run Intel's many KornShell automation scripts on Windows was identified as a key capability.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Internally, Microsoft began an effort to create a Windows port of Korn Shell, which was code-named Kermit.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Intel ultimately pivoted to a Linux-based development platform that could run on Intel CPUs, rendering the Kermit project redundant.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] However, with a fully funded team, Microsoft program manager Jeffrey Snover realized there was an opportunity to create a more general-purpose solution to Microsoft's problem of administrative automation.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] By 2002, Microsoft had started to develop a new approach to command-line management, including a CLI called Monad (also known as Microsoft Shell or MSH).
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The ideas behind it were published in August 2002 in a white paper called the "Monad Manifesto" by its chief architect, Jeffrey Snover.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In a 2017 interview, Snover explains the genesis of PowerShell, saying that he had been trying to make Unix tools available on Windows, which didn't work due to "core architectural difference[s] between Windows and Linux".
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Specifically, he noted that Linux considers everything a text file, whereas Windows considers everything an "API that returns structured data".
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] They were fundamentally incompatible, which led him to take a different approach.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Monad was to be a new extensible CLI with a fresh design capable of automating a range of core administrative tasks.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Microsoft first demonstrated Monad publicly at the Professional Development Conference in Los Angeles in October 2003.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A few months later, they opened up private beta, which eventually led to a public beta.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Microsoft published the first Monad public beta release on June 17, 2005, and the Beta 2 on September 11, 2005, and Beta 3 on January 10, 2006.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] On April 25, 2006, two and a half years after the initial Monad announcement, Microsoft announced that Monad had been renamed **Windows PowerShell**, positioning it as a significant part of its management technology offerings.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Release Candidate (RC) 1 of PowerShell was released at the same time.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A significant aspect of both the name change and the RC was that this was now a component of Windows, rather than a mere add-on.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The final 1.0 version was included as part of Windows Vista.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Release Candidate 2 of PowerShell version 1 was released on September 26, 2006, with final release to the web on November 14, 2006.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell for earlier versions of Windows was released on January 30, 2007.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell v2.0 development began before PowerShell v1.0 shipped.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] During the development, Microsoft shipped three community technology previews (CTP).
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Microsoft made these releases available to the public.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The last CTP release of Windows PowerShell v2.0 was made available in December 2008.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell v2.0 was completed and released to manufacturing in August 2009, as an integral part of Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Versions of PowerShell for Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008 were released in October 2009 and are available for download for both 32-bit and 64-bit platforms.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In an October 2009 issue of *TechNet Magazine*, Microsoft called proficiency with PowerShell "the single most important skill a Windows administrator will need in the coming years".
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Windows 10 shipped with Pester, a script validation suite for PowerShell.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] On August 18, 2016, Microsoft announced that they had made PowerShell open-source and cross-platform with support for Windows, macOS, CentOS and Ubuntu.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The source code was published on GitHub.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The move to open source created a second incarnation of PowerShell called "PowerShell Core", which runs on .NET Core.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] It is distinct from "Windows PowerShell", which runs on the full .NET Framework.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Starting with version 5.1, PowerShell Core is bundled with Windows Server 2016 Nano Server.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A project named *Pash*, a pun on the widely known "bash" Unix shell, has been an open-source and cross-platform reimplementation of PowerShell via the Mono framework.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Pash was created by Igor Moochnick, written in C# and was released under the GNU General Public License.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Pash development stalled in 2008, was restarted on GitHub in 2012, and finally ceased in 2016 when PowerShell was officially made open-source and cross-platform.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A key design goal for PowerShell was to leverage the large number of APIs that already existed in Windows, Windows Management Instrumentation, .NET Framework, and other software.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell cmdlets generally wrap and expose existing functionality instead of implementing new functionality.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The intent was to provide an administrator-friendly, more-consistent interface between administrators and a wide range of underlying functionality.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] With PowerShell, an administrator doesn't need to know .NET, WMI, or low-level API coding, and can instead focus on using the cmdlets exposed by PowerShell.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In this regard, PowerShell creates little new functionality, instead focusing on making existing functionality more accessible to a particular audience.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell's developers based the core grammar of the tool on that of the POSIX 1003.2 KornShell.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] However, PowerShell's language was also influenced by PHP, Perl, and many other existing languages.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] If a command is a standalone executable program, PowerShell launches it in a separate process; if it is a cmdlet, it executes in the PowerShell process.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell provides an interactive command-line interface, where the commands can be entered and their output displayed.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The user interface offers customizable tab completion.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell enables the creation of *aliases* for cmdlets, which PowerShell textually translates into invocations of the original commands.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell supports both named and positional parameters for commands.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In executing a cmdlet, the job of binding the argument value to the parameter is done by PowerShell itself, but for external executables, arguments are parsed by the external executable independently of PowerShell interpretation.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The PowerShell *Extended Type System* (*ETS*) is based on the .NET type system, but with extended semantics (for example, propertySets and third-party extensibility).
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] For example, it enables the creation of different views of objects by exposing only a subset of the data fields, properties, and methods, as well as specifying custom formatting and sorting behavior.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] These views are mapped to the original object using XML-based configuration files.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A cmdlet is a .NET class that derives either from `Cmdlet` or from `PSCmdlet`; the latter is used when it needs to interact with the PowerShell runtime.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The base classes specify methods – `BeginProcessing()`, `ProcessRecord()` and `EndProcessing()` – which a cmdlet overrides to provide functionality based on the events that these functions represent.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] `ProcessRecord()` is called if the object receives pipeline input.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] If a collection of objects is piped, the method is invoked for each object in the collection.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The cmdlet class must have the attribute `CmdletAttribute` which specifies the verb and the noun that make up the name of the cmdlet.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A cmdlet name follows a *Verb-Noun* naming pattern, such as *Get-ChildItem*, which tends to make it self-documented.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] If a cmdlet receives either pipeline input or command-line parameter input, there must be a corresponding property in the class, with a mutator implementation.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell invokes the mutator with the parameter value or pipeline input, which is saved by the mutator implementation in class variables.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] These values are then referred to by the methods which implement the functionality.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Properties that map to command-line parameters are marked by `ParameterAttribute` and are set before the call to `BeginProcessing()`.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Those which map to pipeline input are also flanked by `ParameterAttribute`, but with the `ValueFromPipeline` attribute parameter set.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A cmdlet can use any .NET API and may be written in any .NET language.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In addition, PowerShell makes certain APIs available, such as `WriteObject()`, which is used to access PowerShell-specific functionality, such as writing objects to the pipeline.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A cmdlet can use .NET a data access API directly or use the PowerShell infrastructure of *Providers*, which make data stores addressable using unique paths.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Data stores are exposed using drive letters, and hierarchies within them, addressed as directories.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell ships with providers for the file system, registry, the certificate store, as well as the namespaces for command aliases, variables, and functions.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell also includes various cmdlets for managing various Windows systems, including the file system, or using Windows Management Instrumentation to control Windows components.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Other applications can register cmdlets with PowerShell, thus allowing it to manage them, and, if they enclose any datastore (such as a database), they can add specific providers as well.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A cmdlet can be added to the shell via modules or before v2 snap-ins.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Users are not limited to the cmdlets included in the base PowerShell installation.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] To enable pipeline semantics, similar to the Unix pipeline, a cmdlet receives input and outputs result as objects.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] If a cmdlet outputs multiple objects, each object of the collection is passed through the pipeline before the next object is processed.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A PowerShell pipeline enables complex logic using the pipe (`|`) operator to connect stages.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] However, the PowerShell pipeline differs from Unix pipelines in that stages execute *within* the PowerShell runtime rather than as a set of processes coordinated by the operating system.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Additionally, structured .NET objects, rather than byte streams, are passed from one stage to the next.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Using objects and executing stages within the PowerShell runtime eliminates the need to serialize data structures, or to extract them by explicitly parsing text output.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] An object can also encapsulate certain functions that work on the contained data, which become available to the recipient command for use.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] For the last cmdlet in a pipeline, PowerShell automatically pipes its output object to the `Out-Default` cmdlet, which transforms the objects into a stream of format objects and then renders those to the screen.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Because a PowerShell object is a .NET object, it has a `.ToString()` method which is used to serialize object state.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In addition, PowerShell allows formatting definitions to be specified, so the text representation of objects can be customized by choosing which data elements to display, and in what manner.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] However, in order to maintain backward compatibility, if an external executable is used in a pipeline, it receives a text stream representing the object, instead of directly integrating with the PowerShell type system.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell includes a dynamically typed language for scripting which can implement complex operations using cmdlets imperatively.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The language supports variables, functions, branching (`if-then-else`), loops (`while`, `do`, `for`, and `foreach`), structured error/exception handling and closures/lambda expressions, as well as integration with .NET.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Variables in PowerShell scripts are prefixed with `$`.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Variables can be assigned any value, including the output of cmdlets.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Strings can be enclosed either in single quotes or in double quotes: when using double quotes, variables will be expanded even if they are inside the quotation marks.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Enclosing the path to a file in braces preceded by a dollar sign (as in `${C:\foo.txt}`), known as namespace variable notation, creates a reference to the contents of the file.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] If it is used as an L-value, anything assigned to it will be written to the file.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] When used as an R-value, the contents of the file will be read.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] If an object is assigned, it is serialized before being stored.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Object members can be accessed using `.` notation, as in C# syntax.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell provides special variables, such as `$args`, which is an array of all the command-line arguments passed to a function from the command line, and `$_`, which refers to the current object in the pipeline.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell also provides arrays and associative arrays.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The PowerShell language also evaluates arithmetic expressions entered on the command line immediately, and it parses common abbreviations, such as GB, MB, and KB.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Using the `function` keyword, PowerShell provides for the creation of functions.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] However, PowerShell allows for advanced functions that support named parameters, positional parameters, switch parameters and dynamic parameters.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell allows any static .NET methods to be called by providing their namespaces enclosed in brackets (`[]`), and then using a pair of colons (`::`) to indicate the static method.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] There are dozens of ways to create objects in PowerShell.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Once created, one can access the properties and instance methods of an object using the `.` notation.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell accepts strings, both raw and escaped.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A string enclosed between single quotation marks is a raw string while a string enclosed between double quotation marks is an escaped string.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell treats straight and curly quotes as equivalent.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] For error handling, PowerShell provides a .NET-based exception-handling mechanism.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In case of errors, objects containing information about the error (`Exception` object) are thrown, which are caught using the `try ... catch` construct (although a `trap` construct is supported as well).
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell can be configured to silently resume execution, without actually throwing the exception; this can be done either on a single command, a single session or perpetually.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Scripts written using PowerShell can be made to persist across sessions in either a `.ps1` file or a `.psm1` file (the latter is used to implement a module).
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Later, either the entire script or individual functions in the script can be used.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Scripts and functions operate analogously with cmdlets, in that they can be used as commands in pipelines, and parameters can be bound to them.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Pipeline objects can be passed between functions, scripts, and cmdlets seamlessly.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] To prevent unintentional running of scripts, script execution is disabled by default and must be enabled explicitly.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Enabling of scripts can be performed either at system, user or session level.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell scripts can be signed to verify their integrity, and are subject to Code Access Security.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The PowerShell language supports binary prefix notation similar to the scientific notation supported by many programming languages in the C-family.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] One can also use PowerShell embedded in a management application, which uses the PowerShell runtime to implement the management functionality.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] For this, PowerShell provides a managed hosting API.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Via the APIs, the application can instantiate a *runspace* (one instantiation of the PowerShell runtime), which runs in the application's process and is exposed as a `Runspace` object.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The state of the runspace is encased in a `SessionState` object.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] When the runspace is created, the PowerShell runtime initializes the instantiation, including initializing the providers and enumerating the cmdlets, and updates the `SessionState` object accordingly.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The Runspace then must be opened for either synchronous processing or asynchronous processing.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] After that it can be used to execute commands.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] To execute a command, a pipeline (represented by a `Pipeline` object) must be created and associated with the runspace.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The pipeline object is then populated with the cmdlets that make up the pipeline.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] For sequential operations (as in a PowerShell script), a Pipeline object is created for each statement and nested inside another Pipeline object.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The types are verified and parameters bound using reflection.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Once the pipeline is set up, the host calls the `Invoke()` method to run the commands, or its asynchronous equivalent, `InvokeAsync()`.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] If the pipeline has the `Write-Host` cmdlet at the end of the pipeline, it writes the result onto the console screen.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] If not, the results are handed over to the host, which might either apply further processing or display the output itself.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Microsoft Exchange Server 2007 uses the hosting APIs to provide its management GUI.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Each operation exposed in the GUI is mapped to a sequence of PowerShell commands (or pipelines).
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The host creates the pipeline and executes them.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In fact, the interactive PowerShell console itself is a PowerShell host, which interprets the scripts entered at command line and creates the necessary `Pipeline` objects and invokes them.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] DSC allows for declaratively specifying how a software environment should be configured.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Upon running a *configuration*, DSC will ensure that the system gets the state described in the configuration.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The *Local Configuration Manager* (LCM) periodically polls the system using the control flow described by *resources* (imperative pieces of DSC) to make sure that the state of a configuration is maintained.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] All major releases are still supported, and each major release has featured backwards compatibility with preceding versions.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Initially using the code name "Monad", PowerShell was first shown publicly at the Professional Developers Conference in October 2003 in Los Angeles.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Named Windows PowerShell, version 1.0 was released in November 2006 for Windows XP SP2, Windows Server 2003 SP1 and Windows Vista and as an optional component of Windows Server 2008.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 2.0 integrates with Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 and is released for Windows XP with Service Pack 3, Windows Server 2003 with Service Pack 2, and Windows Vista with Service Pack 1.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The version includes changes to the language and hosting API, in addition to including more than 240 new cmdlets.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 3.0 integrates with Windows 8, Windows Server 2012, Windows 7 with Service Pack 1, Windows Server 2008 with Service Pack 1, and Windows Server 2008 R2 with Service Pack 1.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 3.0 is part of a larger package, Windows Management Framework 3.0 (WMF3), which also contains the WinRM service to support remoting.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Microsoft made several Community Technology Preview releases of WMF3.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] An early community technology preview 2 (CTP 2) version of Windows Management Framework 3.0 was released on December 2, 2011.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Windows Management Framework 3.0 was released for general availability in December 2012 and is included with Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012 by default.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 4.0 integrates with Windows 8.1, Windows Server 2012 R2, Windows 7 SP1, Windows Server 2008 R2 SP1 and Windows Server 2012.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 5.0 was re-released with Windows Management Framework (WMF) 5.0 on February 24, 2016, following an initial release with a severe bug.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 5.1 was released along with the Windows 10 Anniversary Update on August 2, 2016, and in Windows Server 2016.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PackageManagement now supports proxies, PSReadLine now has ViMode support, and two new cmdlets were added: Get-TimeZone and Set-TimeZone.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The LocalAccounts module allows for adding/removing local user accounts.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] A preview for was released for Windows 7, Windows Server 2008, Windows Server 2008 R2, Windows Server 2012, and Windows Server 2012 R2 on July 16, 2016, and was released on January 19, 2017.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 5.1 is the first to come in two editions of "Desktop" and "Core".
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The "Desktop" edition is the continuation product line that uses the .NET Framework, and the "Core" edition runs on .NET Core and is bundled with Windows Server 2016 Nano Server.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In exchange for smaller footprint, the latter lacks some features such as the cmdlets to manage clipboard or join a computer to a domain, WMI version 1 cmdlets, Event Log cmdlets and profiles.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] This was the final version exclusively for Windows.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 5.1 remains pre-installed on Windows 10, Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022, while the .NET version needs to be installed separately and can run side-by-side with the .NET Framework version.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Renamed to PowerShell Core, version 6.0 was first announced on August 18, 2016, when Microsoft unveiled its decision to make the product cross-platform, independent of Windows, free and open source.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] It achieved general availability on January 10, 2018, for Windows, macOS and Linux.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] It has its own support lifecycle and adheres to the Microsoft lifecycle policy that is introduced with Windows 10: Only the latest version of PowerShell Core is supported.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Microsoft expects to release one minor version for PowerShell Core 6.0 every six months.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The most significant change in this version is the expansion to the other platforms.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] For Windows administrators, this version did not include any major new features.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In an interview with the community on January 11, 2018, the development team was asked to list the top 10 most exciting things that would happen for a Windows IT professional who would migrate from version 5.1 to version 6.0.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] In response, Angel Calvo of Microsoft could only name two: cross-platform and open-source.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] PowerShell 6 changed to UTF-8 as default encoding, with some exceptions.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] According to Microsoft, one of the new features of version 6.1 is "Compatibility with 1900+ existing cmdlets in Windows 10 and Windows Server 2019." Still, no details of these cmdlets can be found in the full version of the change log.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Microsoft later professes that this number was insufficient as PowerShell Core failed to replace Windows PowerShell 5.1 and gain traction on Windows.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 6.2 is focused primarily on performance improvements, bug fixes, and smaller cmdlet and language enhancements that improved developer productivity.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Renamed to simply PowerShell, version 7 replaces the previous product lines: PowerShell Core and Windows PowerShell.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The focus in development was to make version 7 a viable replacement for version 5.1, i.e. to have near parity with it in terms of compatibility with modules that ship with Windows.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 7.2 is the next long-term support version, after version 7.0.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] It uses .NET 6.0 and features universal installer packages for Linux.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] On Windows, updates to version 7.2 and later come via the Microsoft Update service; this feature has been missing from versions 6.0 through 7.1.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 7.3 includes some general Cmdlet updates and fixes, testing for framework dependent package in release pipeline as well as build and packaging improvements.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 7.4 is based on .NET 8 and is considered the long term support (LTS) release.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 7.5 is the latest stable release, released January 2025; it was built on .NET 9.0.1.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] It includes enhancements for performance, usability, and security.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Key updates include improvements to tab completion, such as better type inference and new argument completers, as well as fixes for Invoke-WebRequest and Invoke-RestMethod.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] This release also adds the new ConvertTo-CliXml and ConvertFrom-CliXml cmdlets, and updates core modules like PSReadLine and Microsoft.PowerShell.PSResourceGet.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Breaking changes include updates to Test-Path parameter handling, and default settings for New-FileCatalog.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Prior to GA Release there were 5 preview releases and 1 RC release of PowerShell v7.5.0, with a full release blog post for this version expected soon.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Version 7.6 is based on .NET 9 and is the latest release.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] The following table contains various cmdlets that ship with PowerShell that have notably similar functionality to commands in other shells.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] Many of these cmdlets are exposed to the user via predefined aliases to make their use familiar to users of the other shells.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] *fc* is defined in the POSIX standard and **history** is not.
[src:powershell-deep/cmdlet] However most Unix implementations also define **history**.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:powershell-deep/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:powershell-deep/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] An operating system **shell** is a computer program that provides relatively broad and direct access to the system on which it runs.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] The term *shell* refers to how it is a relatively thin layer around an operating system.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Most shells are command-line interface (CLI) programs.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Some graphical user interfaces (GUI) also include shells.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Operating systems provide various services to their users, including file management, process management (running and terminating applications), batch processing, and operating system monitoring and configuration.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Most operating system shells are not *direct* interfaces to the underlying kernel, even if a shell communicates with the user via peripheral devices attached to the computer directly.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Shells are actually special applications that use the kernel API in just the same way as it is used by other application programs.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] A shell manages the user–system interaction by prompting users for input, interpreting their input, and then handling output from the underlying operating system (much like a read–eval–print loop, REPL).
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Since the operating system shell is actually an application, it may easily be replaced with another similar application for most operating systems.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] In addition to shells running on local systems, there are different ways to make remote systems available to local users; such approaches are usually referred to as remote access or remote administration.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Initially available on multi-user mainframes, which provided text-based UIs for each active user *simultaneously* by means of a text terminal connected to the mainframe via serial line or modem, remote access has extended to Unix-like systems and Microsoft Windows.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] On Unix-like systems, Secure Shell protocol (SSH) is usually used for text-based shells, while SSH tunneling can be used for X Window System–based graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] On Microsoft Windows, Remote Desktop Protocol can be used to provide GUI remote access, since Windows Vista, PowerShell Remote, since Windows 10 build 1809 SSH can also be used for text-based remote access via WMI, RPC, and WS-Management.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Most operating system shells fall into one of two categories – command-line and graphical.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Command-line shells provide a command-line interface (CLI) to the operating system, while graphical shells provide a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Other possibilities, although not so common, include a voice user interface and various implementations of a text-based user interface (TUI) that are not CLI, such as text-based menu systems.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] The relative merits of CLI- and GUI-based shells are often debated.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Many computer users use both depending on the task to be performed.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Early interactive systems provided a simple command-line interpreter as part of the resident monitor.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] This interpreter might be called by different names, such as `COMCON` on DEC TOPS-10 systems.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] The interpreter would execute one of a number of predefined commands, one of which would be to run a user program.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Common commands would log the user on and off the system, allocate, free, and manipulate devices and files, and query various pieces of information about the system or a user process.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] In 1964, for the Multics operating system, Louis Pouzin conceived the idea of "using commands somehow like a programming language," and coined the term *shell* to describe it.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] In a 1965 document, the shell is defined as "a common procedure called automatically by the supervisor whenever a user types in some message at his console, at a time when he has no other process in active execution under console control.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] This procedure acts as an interface between console messages and subroutine [in the supervisor]." This system was first implemented by Glenda Schroeder and an unnamed man from General Electric.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Multics also introduced the *active function*, a key concept in some later shells.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] In 1971, Ken Thompson developed the Thompson shell in the first version of Unix.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] While simpler than the Multics shell, it contained some innovative features, which have been carried forward in modern shells, including the use of < and > for input and output redirection.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] The graphical shell first appeared in Douglas Engelbart’s NLS system, demonstrated in December, 1968 at the Fall Joint Computer Conference in San Francisco, in what has been called *The Mother of All Demos*.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Engelbart’s colleagues at Stanford Research Institute brought the concept to the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC), where it appeared on the Alto, introduced in 1973.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] From there the idea spread to Niklaus Wirth’s Lilith in 1980, and the Apple Lisa in 1983, then became ubiquitous.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] A command-line interface (CLI) is an operating system shell that uses alphanumeric characters typed on a keyboard to provide instructions and data to the operating system, interactively.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Operating systems such as UNIX have a large variety of shell programs with different commands, syntax and capabilities, with the POSIX shell being a baseline.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Application programs may also implement a command-line interface.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] For example, in Unix-like systems, the telnet program has a number of commands for controlling a link to a remote computer system.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Since the commands to the program are made of the same keystrokes as the data being sent to a remote computer, some means of distinguishing the two are required.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] An escape sequence can be defined, using either a special local keystroke that is never passed on but always interpreted by the local system.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] The program becomes modal, switching between interpreting commands from the keyboard or passing keystrokes on as data to be processed.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] A feature of many command-line shells is the ability to save sequences of commands for re-use.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] A data file can contain sequences of commands which the CLI can be made to follow as if typed in by a user.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Special features in the CLI may apply when it is carrying out these stored instructions.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Such batch files (script files) can be used repeatedly to automate routine operations such as initializing a set of programs when a system is restarted.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Batch mode use of shells usually involves structures, conditionals, variables, and other elements of programming languages; some have the bare essentials needed for such a purpose, others are very sophisticated programming languages in and of themselves.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Conversely, some programming languages can be used interactively from an operating system shell or in a purpose-built program.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Several command-line shells, such as Nushell, Xonsh, Bash (Unix shell), and Z shell, offer command-line completion, enabling the interpreter to expand commands based on a few characters input by the user.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] A command-line interpreter may offer a history function, so that the user can recall earlier commands issued to the system and repeat them, possibly with some editing.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Since all commands to the operating system had to be typed by the user, short command names and compact systems for representing program options were common.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Short names were sometimes hard for a user to recall, and early systems lacked the storage resources to provide a detailed on-line user instruction guide.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] A graphical user interface (GUI) provides means for manipulating programs graphically, by allowing for operations such as opening, closing, moving and resizing windows, as well as switching focus between windows.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Graphical shells may be included with desktop environments or come separately, even as a set of loosely coupled utilities.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Most graphical user interfaces develop the metaphor of an "electronic desktop", where data files are represented as if they were paper documents on a desk, and application programs similarly have graphical representations instead of being invoked by command names.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Graphical shells typically build on top of a windowing system.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] GNOME shell and KDE Plasma are graphical shells for the X Window System and Wayland.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] In the case of macOS, Quartz Compositor acts as the windowing system, and the shell consists of the Finder, the Dock, SystemUIServer, and Mission Control.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Modern versions of the Microsoft Windows operating system use the Windows shell as their shell.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Windows Shell provides desktop environment, start menu, and task bar, as well as a graphical user interface for accessing the file management functions of the operating system.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Older versions also include Program Manager, which was the shell for the 3.x series of Microsoft Windows, and which in fact shipped with later versions of Windows of both the 95 and NT types at least through Windows XP.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] The interfaces of Windows versions 1 and 2 were markedly different.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Desktop applications are also considered shells, as long as they use a third-party engine.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Likewise, many individuals and developers dissatisfied with the interface of Windows Explorer have developed software that either alters the functioning and appearance of the shell or replaces it entirely.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] WindowBlinds by StarDock is a good example of the former sort of application.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] LiteStep and Emerge Desktop are good examples of the latter.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Interoperability programmes and purpose-designed software lets Windows users use equivalents of many of the various Unix-based GUIs discussed below, as well as Macintosh.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] An equivalent of the OS/2 Presentation Manager for version 3.0 can run some OS/2 programmes under some conditions using the OS/2 environmental subsystem in versions of Windows NT.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] A shell can usually also be invoked from within a program through standard system functions like `system()`, `popen()` and `exec()` without any user interface being involved.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Beyond these standard functions, Windows for example provides the "Windows Shell API" which exposes a set of functions that programs can use to interact with the Windows shell.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] These shell functions are provided in DLL's (like shell32.dll and shlwapi.dll) and do not need the default Windows shell GUI i.e. explorer.exe to be running.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Explorer.exe and its replacements generally make use of the Windows Shell API to provide users with a Windows shell GUI without having to implement themselves the Windows shell core functionalities (which are implemented and provided by shell32.dll and shlwapi.dll).
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] But programs can use the Windows Shell API for other purposes and without providing users with a shell user interface.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] "Shell" is also used loosely to describe application software that is "built around" a particular component, such as web browsers and email clients, in analogy to the shells found in nature.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] Indeed, the (command-line) shell encapsulates the operating system *kernel*.
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] These are also sometimes referred to as "wrappers".
[src:powershell-deep/shell-computing] In expert systems, a shell is a piece of software that is an "empty" expert system without the knowledge base for any particular application.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] WMI allows scripting languages (such as VBScript or PowerShell) to manage Microsoft Windows personal computers and servers, both locally and remotely.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] WMI comes preinstalled in Windows 2000 and later.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] It is available as a download for Windows NT 4.0, Windows 95, and Windows 98.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] Also included with Windows was **Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line** (**WMIC**), a CLI utility to interface with WMI.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] However, starting with Windows 10, version 21H1 and Windows Server 2022, WMIC is deprecated in favor of PowerShell.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The purpose of WMI is to define a proprietary set of environment-independent specifications that enable sharing management information between management apps.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] WMI prescribes enterprise management standards and related technologies for Windows that work with existing management standards, such as Desktop Management Interface (DMI) and Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] WMI complements these other standards by providing a uniform model for accessing management data from any source.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] Because WMI abstracts the manageable entities with Common Information Model (CIM) and a collection of providers, the development of a provider implies several steps.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] Many customers have interpreted the growth in numbers of providers as a sign that Microsoft envisions WMI as the ubiquitous management layer of Windows.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] This enables administrators who lack WMI coding skills to benefit from WMI.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] WMI offers many features out of the box.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] To speed up the process of writing a WMI provider, the WMI team developed the *WMI ATL Wizard* to generate the code template implementing a provider.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The code generated is based on the WMI class model initially designed by the developer.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The WMI provider developer will be able to interface the pre-defined COM or DCOM interfaces for the WMI provider with its set of native APIs retrieving the management information to expose.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] WMI is based on an industry standard called Common Information Model (CIM) defined by the Distributed Management Task Force (DMTF).
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The CIM class-based schema is defined by a consortium of manufacturers and software developers for the requirements of the industry.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] Any developer can write code that fits into this model.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] For instance, Intel develops WMI providers for its network adapters.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] HP leveraged existing WMI providers and developed custom WMI providers for its OpenView enterprise management solutions.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] IBM's Tivoli management suite consumes WMI.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] Starting with Windows XP SP2, Microsoft leverages WMI to get status information from antivirus software and firewalls.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] On the Windows NT family of operating systems, WMI runs as a Windows service called `WinMgmt`.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] On the Windows 9x family, WMI runs in the context of the `WinMgmt.exe` executable file.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] On both Windows 9x and Windows NT families, `WinMgmt.exe` is available as a command-line utility for servicing the WMI repository.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] In the .NET Framework, the ManagementClass class represents a Common Information Model (CIM) management class.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] A WMI class can be a `Win32_LogicalDisk` in the case of a disk drive, or a `Win32_Process`, such as a running program like `Notepad.exe`.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The `MSNdis_80211_ServiceSetIdentifier` WMI class is only supported on Windows XP and Windows Server 2003.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The WMI extensions to WDM provide kernel-level instrumentation such as publishing information, configuring device settings, supplying event notification from device drivers, and allowing administrators to set data security through a WMI provider known as the *WDM provider*.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The extensions are part of the WDM architecture; however, they have broad utility and can be used with other types of drivers as well (such as SCSI and NDIS).
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The WMI Driver Extensions service monitors all drivers and event trace providers that are configured to publish WMI or event trace information.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] Instrumented hardware data is provided by way of drivers instrumented for WMI extensions for WDM.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] WMI extensions for WDM offer a set of Windows device driver interfaces for instrumenting data within the driver models native to Windows, so OEMs and IHVs can easily extend the instrumented data set and add value to a hardware/software solution.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] The WMI Driver Extensions, however, are not supported by Windows Vista and later operating systems.
[src:powershell-deep/windows-management-instrumentation] Performance Monitor and AIDA64 are examples to using WMI to get some operating system monitoring information.
